The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Rao in intensive cardiac care

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 Narasimha Rao

 New Delhi, Dec. 10: Former 

 Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao was said to be critical 

 after he suffered a heart attack at the All India Institute 

 of Medical Sciences, where he was rushed early this morning 

 after feeling ill.

 The hospital authorities are closely monitoring the condition of the 83-year-old Congress leader who is in the intensive cardiac care unit of the AIIMS? cardiothoracic centre.

 Rao was taken to hospital at 2 am after he complained of breathlessness and chest pain. He has a history of heart problems.

 An AIIMS statement said the former Prime Minister was admitted with a complaint of breathlessness. He improved on treatment and spent a restful night. After breakfast, he went back to sleep.

 Rao, while asleep, experienced a cardiac arrest because of electrical disturbances in the heart rhythm and was successfully revived, the statement said.

 The former Prime Minister?s blood pressure and heart rate are stable but he requires intensive care and monitoring, it added.

 Rao was visited at the hospital by Congress chief Sonia Gandhi, Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, health minister Anbumani Ramadoss, former Prime Ministers Atal Bihari Vajpayee and Chandrasekhar, and Telugu Desam Party leader Yerran Naidu.

 Home minister Shivraj Patil and urban development minister Ghulam Nabi Azad, too, called on the ailing leader.

 Asked about the former Prime Minister?s condition, Patil said: ?According to doctors, his kidneys and heart are now functioning normally though he is under tranquilliser.? Asked if Rao could be considered out of danger, he replied in the affirmative. 

 Rao has been ailing for some time 

 with problems related to diabetes, coronary heart disease 

 and other vascular diseases, and pulmonary fibriosis.




